body: It's stored on azure central us and ncus data center.. and we use aria2c and curl for accessing it

If I access it from SCUS Azure, it can reach ~500Mbps.
But outside Microsoft network it's barely reachable (Will take ridiculously long, and with high chance of non-resumable connection lost)
I wonder if it's better to put it simply as the Release assert on GitHub.
They got nice CDN.
@snnn do we have any security concern on hosting the test data on outside site?

For the files under https://onnxruntimetestdata.blob.core.windows.net/models, no. They are public.
However, our ci build won't fetch the data from github.  It's like, when you live in the U.S., you won't go to Microsoft's Beijing cafeteria for lunch.

Haha but that makes it less friendly to the open source community.
What I'm proposing is more like `wget azure` in CI file only + `wget -c github` in general script, which means the second step basically does nothing in your CI.

rename.from: Extremely Slow Download Speed of Test Data
rename.to: Extremely Slow Download Speed of Test Data in China

body: Does our subscription include Azure's China region?
No. China is totally different. For example, your U.S. Amazon account can't be used in Amazon China. The same thing applies to Azure.

The data set is quite large and probably not well suited to be hosted in github. The azure blob store is publicly accessible and @raymondxyang will update the documentation to include the link. If this is only a non-blocking inconvenience for users physically located in China, then this is a low priority fix for us at this time. This should mostly be a one-time cost to download the data for anyone that needs it.

Hi @xkszltl the data is hosted in central us. I live in the west coast. I can download the data at full internet speed. If you are having connectivity issue with Azure blob storage, please feel free to contact Azure networking team. 
 
 And also, I would suggest you use the tools provided by Azure blob storage team. For example, azcopy. It has very good retry and error recovery function.
azcopy is probably a good suggestion. Thanks!

FYI I did a curl in Redmond office just now, after normal working hours so no much traffic to interfere with.
Here's the speed pattern:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5203025/60230847-25c33f80-984c-11e9-867a-3a8ac57d1c33.png)
So around 100-130Mbps, with valleys every few seconds.

Machine is connected with GE network and I can certainly reach line speed during my daily work.
